    <h2>Who Is Siberia?</h2>
    <p>Siberia is not just a brand; it's a <strong>cult moment in nicotine pouch history</strong>. Launched in the mid-2000s by GN Tobacco (Swedish Match heritage), Siberia became synonymous with "extreme strength" and defined the category that still exists today. Users don't try Siberia casually. They arrive at Siberia after a journey: <a href="/blog/best-nicotine-pouches-for-beginners-2026">light strengths</a>, medium strengths, and finally the decision: "I'm ready for legendary status." For context on where Siberia sits in the wider market, see our <a href="/blog/strongest-nicotine-pouches-ranked-2026">strength ranking guide</a>.</p>
    <p>Siberia's cult appeal is real. Reddit communities discuss it. WhatsApp groups debate it. Users who handle Siberia comfortably wear it as a badge. It's not rational. It's tribal. And it's part of why Siberia remains the benchmark all competitors reference.</p>

    <h2>The -80°C Experience: What Is It Really?</h2>
    <p>Let's address the elephant: <strong>-80°C does not mean the pouch is frozen.</strong> It's a marketing metaphor for the cooling sensation. Here's the reality:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Siberia pouches are room temperature when you place them.</li>
        <li>The cooling effect comes from <strong>natural mint compounds</strong> and the pouch formula.</li>
        <li>Your mouth's nerve sensors interpret the cooling as "-80°C intense" — a sensory metaphor, not literal temperature.</li>
        <li>It's the same principle as mint toothpaste feeling "cool" without actual freezing.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>So when users describe a -80°C hit, they're describing <strong>extreme minty cooling intensity</strong> — a powerful sensation that distinguishes Siberia from standard mint brands. It's theatre, yes, but effective theatre backed by real sensory science.</p>

