    <h2>Strength Tiers Explained</h2>

    <h3>Entry Tier: Ultra Slim (16.5 mg)</h3>
    <p>If you've handled <a href="/blog/white-fox-nicotine-pouches-complete-guide">White Fox's 16.5 mg Full Charge</a> comfortably for weeks, Ultra Slim is your Siberia gateway. The pouch is slender, the strength is powerful, and the cooling is noticeable. This is where you discover whether Siberia's legend lives up to hype. For many, Ultra Slim becomes the daily workhorse. For others, it's a stepping stone.</p>
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Users proven comfortable with 16+ mg who want to test Siberia without committing to maximum strength.</p>

    <h3>Compact Tier: Mini (21.5 mg) & Super Slim (21.5 mg)</h3>
    <p>Both hit 21.5 mg nicotine, but offer different formats:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Mini:</strong> Compact pouch, oral comfort, concentrated intensity.</li>
        <li><strong>Super Slim:</strong> Thin pouch, discreet, also 21.5 mg but spread across a thinner form.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>These are the "stepping stones" tier. You're building tolerance progressively. Maxi is not your destination — you're exploring intermediate strength in manageable formats.</p>
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Transitional users moving 16.5 mg → 25+ mg; users exploring format preference.</p>

    <h3>Expert Tier: Slim (25 mg)</h3>
    <p>This is the <strong>unofficial Siberia sweet spot</strong> for daily users. At 25 mg, you're serious enough to feel legendary status, but not so extreme that tolerance spirals uncontrollably. The slim format keeps oral comfort high. The nicotine hit is undeniable. Most Siberia users who report "daily rotation" are actually running Slim repeatedly.</p>
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Experienced users maintaining Siberia use; ex-smokers who've graduated from moderate brands; users who want serious strength without the extreme persona.</p>

    <h3>Extreme Tier: Portion (33 mg) & Long Portion (35 mg)</h3>
    <p>You've entered specialist territory. At 33–35 mg, nicotine poisoning risk increases noticeably. Format matters:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Portion (33 mg):</strong> Standard traditional format, maximum practical pouch size.</li>
        <li><strong>Long Portion (35 mg):</strong> Extended session version; sustained 35 mg hit over longer duration.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Users at this tier are often testing limits, chasing novelty, or have genuinely exceptional tolerance. Not for daily rotation.</p>
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Occasional extreme sessions; tolerance specialists; users explicitly seeking the "legendary extreme" experience.</p>

    <h3>Absolute Maximum: Maxi All White (49.5 mg)</h3>
    <p>This is not a daily pouch. This is the <strong>ultimate status symbol</strong> in the nicotine pouch world. At 49.5 mg, you're handling roughly 50 times the nicotine of a light Skruf pouch. The maxi format is large, the hit is overwhelming, and the cooling is intense. For many users, Maxi serves one purpose: the bragging story. "I've handled Siberia Maxi" is a credential in extreme-user communities.</p>
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> One-off extreme sessions; competitive tolerance testing; occasional novelty seekers with proven expert-level tolerance.</p>

    <h2>IMPORTANT: Safety and Nicotine Poisoning Risk</h2>

    <div style="background: #fee2e2; border: 2px solid #dc2626; padding: 20px; margin: 30px 0; border-radius: 4px;">
        <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: #991b1b;">Critical Safety Information</h3>
        <p><strong>Siberia is extreme strength. Nicotine poisoning is real.</strong> Do not take this lightly.</p>
        <h4>Symptoms of Nicotine Poisoning (seek medical attention immediately if you experience):</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Tremors or shaking (hands, legs)</li>
            <li>Dizziness or lightheadedness</li>
            <li>Nausea or vomiting</li>
            <li>Rapid or irregular heartbeat</li>
            <li>Confusion or anxiety</li>
            <li>Excessive salivation</li>
            <li>Seizures (severe cases)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Risk Factors When Using Siberia:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>No tolerance:</strong> Never start with Siberia. Your body needs progressive adaptation.</li>
            <li><strong>Dehydration:</strong> Siberia demands hydration. Drink water consistently. Dehydration amplifies poisoning symptoms.</li>
            <li><strong>Empty stomach:</strong> Nicotine absorption is faster on empty stomach. Eat before using extreme-strength pouches.</li>
            <li><strong>Swallowing saliva:</strong> Don't swallow the saliva repeatedly. Spit regularly. Saliva carries dissolved nicotine.</li>
            <li><strong>Multiple pouches:</strong> Never use more than one Siberia pouch at a time.</li>
            <li><strong>Rapid progression:</strong> Don't jump from 12 mg straight to 25 mg. Progress over weeks, not days.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Safe Usage Guidelines:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Start at Ultra Slim (16.5 mg) <strong>only if</strong> you've used 9+ mg pouches for at least 2–3 months.</li>
            <li>Spend 2–4 weeks at each strength tier before progressing.</li>
            <li>Never exceed one pouch every 4–6 hours initially.</li>
            <li>Discontinue immediately if you experience dizziness, tremors, or nausea.</li>
            <li>Keep emergency phone numbers handy; know your nearest hospital.</li>
            <li>If you have heart conditions, high blood pressure, or take medications, consult your doctor first.</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>Medical Resources:</h4>
        <p><a href="https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/21582-nicotine-poisoning">Cleveland Clinic: Nicotine Poisoning</a> — comprehensive medical information and when to seek emergency care.</p>
    </div>

